{"hitCount": 1, "request": {"cursorMark": "*", "pageSize": 1, "queryString": "DOI:\"10.1002/(sici)1520-636x(1997)9:3<313::aid-chir19>3.0.co;2-q\"", "resultType": "core", "sort": "", "synonym": false}, "resultList": {"result": [{"abstractText": "In vitro experiments to investigate possible stereoselective aspects of the topical administration of ibuprofen have been conducted. Incubation of ibuprofen with rat skin homogenates in the presence of coenzyme A, ATP, and magnesium provided no evidence for the formation of ibuprofenyl coenzyme A (the initial intermediate in the metabolic inversion of [R]- to [S]-ibuprofen). Similar incubation studies gave no indication of a change in the enantiomeric ratios of ibuprofen over the time course of the experiments. Percutaneous penetration studies of ibuprofen gel through porcine skin indicated that the ibuprofen enantiomer levels in the reservoir solutions were consistent with racemic ibuprofen having traversed the skin with no metabolic inversion. These results suggest that, in the models studied, skin metabolism does not result in the chiral inversion of (R)- to (S)-ibuprofen and that the topical administration of ibuprofen will result in the delivery of 50% \"isomeric ballast.\"", "affiliation": "School of Pharmacy, Queen's University of Belfast, Northern Ireland.", "authMan": "N", "authorList": {"author": [{"authorAffiliationDetailsList": {"authorAffiliation": [{"affiliation": "School of Pharmacy, Queen's University of Belfast, Northern Ireland."}]}, "firstName": "J S", "fullName": "Millership JS", "initials": "JS", "lastName": "Millership"}, {"firstName": "P S", "fullName": "Collier PS", "initials": "PS", "lastName": "Collier"}]}, "authorString": "Millership JS, Collier PS.", "chemicalList": {"chemical": [{"name": "Anti-Inflammatory Agents, Non-Steroidal", "registryNumber": "0"}, {"name": "Gels", "registryNumber": "0"}, {"name": "Ibuprofen", "registryNumber": "WK2XYI10QM"}]}, "citedByCount": 1, "dataLinksTagsList": {"dataLi